      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes more sense than before, thanks. you mentioned it \"defies classical intuition\"... i've heard people call it \"spooky\" before. can you elaborate on why it's considered so weird or counter-intuitive compared to how things usually work in the real world?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was famously uneasy with the concept of quantum entanglement. He referred to it as \"spooky\" because it seemed to violate the principles of locality and causality that are fundamental to classical physics. In the classical world, objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings, and information cannot travel faster than the speed of light. This means that changes in one object should not instantaneously affect another object that is far away, as there is no known mechanism for such a direct and immediate influence.\n\nQuantum entanglement, however, suggests that two entangled particles can be correlated in such a way that the state of one particle is instantly reflected in the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. This instantaneous correlation seems to defy the classical understanding of space and time, as it implies that information about the state of one particle is somehow being transmitted to the other particle faster than the speed of light, which is not possible according to the theory of relativity.\n\nThis counter-intuitive nature of quantum entanglement challenges our classical notions of reality and has led to many debates and discussions in the field of physics. It has also been experimentally confirmed,",
      "source": "target",
